John Edward: Language Skills Are Essential to the People of the World
Scotland's independent schools maintain a school record of excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with new outstanding exam results enhanced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) seek to provide the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools are working to prepare their students for higher education, their chosen career and their place as citizens of the world.
As an education sector capable of designing and implementing a school-based curriculum, we see that contemporary languages remain popular and desirable in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, you speak to his heart."
This reminds us that we cannot rely on English to create relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
Looking at the excellent results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the most important success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students studying foreign languages received the highest grade, A.
The data collected from 74 SCIS schools show that 72% of students received the highest rating, A, in Mandarin, as well as 72% of students who studied German, 69% of students who studied French and 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland's independent schools support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Languages as subjects are now organized as are science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the programs of independent schools and other schools.
A survey of the British Employment and Skills Commission carried out in 2014 revealed that 17% of employers' difficulties in recruiting candidates are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more job offers requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of his career choice, a person who speaks a second language will benefit from a real benefit in the future through this sustainable skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners will automatically place the multilingual in front of its competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom, 75% of them did not master a foreign language enough to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those of emerging economies, children will have better chances of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Several of them will focus on classical contemporary languages, while others will teach relevant languages for the United Kingdom in the future of 2020, including Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's preferences, several languages will be available in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills necessary for their success, no matter what their future holds.
It is clear that, in a global business environment, languages remain of paramount importance to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do this.
John Edward is director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
