Harvard: students take rest courses
This year, Harvard University has set up a new course that allows all first-cycle students to sleep more and to fight against the growing machist tendency of studying caffeine all night long.
One professor noted that most of the students at the best university in the world do not know how to take care of them
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first in the United States.
It was after giving a conference on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him
In the end, a student approached me and said, "Why do they tell me that only in the past year?"
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
For the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their school and physical performance, as well as their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and Director General of Health Services at the University, said that the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students had a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The hour of course consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing various objects (coffee rate, curtains, basketball, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical benefits and the importance of integrating a routine before bed.
In another section, participants learn how the lack of long-term sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not instantly change the behaviour of students.
However, we believe that they have the right to know this information - in the same way that you have the right to know what the effects of smoking on health are," said Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the culture of pride of "pasting a white night" still exists, and he adds that the growing pressure and modern technology on students makes sleepiness a growing problem.
Having sufficient and good-quality sleep should be the "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep puts the brain into mode of inanitation, making them hungry permanently.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student in chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He stated that this course had opened his eyes and had pushed him to insist that he be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all third-cycle students to follow a similar curriculum before joining the renowned institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students provide both the time of bedtime and the time of awakening, and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and cause sleeping disorders.
