And now, a page of our Almanach "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE TOURNE ACCOUNT... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that subsequently gave birth to the device known as Geiger meter.
A pillar of science since then, Geiger has also become fundamental in pop culture, as can be seen in the 1950 film " Bells of Coronado", with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man: "What is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to search for radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
Thanks to these listeners, we can actually hear the effects of atoms released into minerals by radioactivity."
Evans: "So say, it's sure to jump there!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd anniversary.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to "detect" cancer cells
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to "detect" and kill cancer cells
As part of the treatment, the vaccine tells the immune system how to recognize cancer cells
This technique consists of extracting and modifying immune cells from a patient into a laboratory
They can then "detect" a protein that is common to many cancers, and are then reinjected
An experimental vaccine shows encouraging results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman who received the vaccine, whose aim is to teach the immune system to recognize cancer cells, has seen her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method consists of extracting and modifying immune cells from a patient into a laboratory, so that they can detect HER2 protein, common to many cancers, and finally re-injecting them.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the American National Cancer Institute based in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine."
According to Professor Berzofsky, the HER2 protein "leads to an increase in several types of cancer", including breast, ovarian, pulmonary and colorectal cancer.
A similar approach, which consists of removing immune cells to "learn" to target cancer cells, has been demonstrated in the treatment of a type of leukaemia.
