HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% of new cases
China reported an increase of 14 per cent of its people with HIV and AIDS.
According to Chinese health authorities, more than 820,000 people are concerned.
Almost 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018.
Most patients were contaminated during sexual intercourse, which is a new fact.
Historically, the virus has spread rapidly in some parts of the country following transfusions of contaminated blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way was virtually zero, said Chinese health authorities at a conference held in Yunnan Province.
However, from year to year, the number of HIV-positive and AIDS-affected people in China has increased by 100,000.
In the Chinese LGBT community, transmission of HIV through sex is a serious problem.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community remains widespread.
Due to the conservative values of the country, studies suggest that 70% to 90% of homosexual men end up marrying a woman.
Many cases of transmission are due to inadequate sexual protection.
As part of its efforts to address this problem, the Chinese government has promised since 2003 universal access to drugs against HIV.
