The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a New Internet to challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a new company that seeks to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee's Solid Free Platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored as well as persons authorized to access such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee said he was joking that Inrupt was intended to "lord the world."
"We have to do it now," he said about the launch.
"It's a historic moment."
The application uses Solid technology to enable people to create their own "online personal data store" or DPL.
It may contain contact lists, task lists, a calendar, a music library, as well as other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify were all available at the same time on one browser.
The particularity of the personal data store online is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what kind of information.
The company calls this "personal responsibility through data".
According to the company's CEO, John Bruce, Inrupt's idea is that the company brings appropriate resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to all.
The company is currently composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few developers working on the project and a community of voluntary co-ordinators.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee has stated that his team and they are not yet in discussion with " Facebook and Google" in order to know whether or not to make a complete change where all their business models are completely camouflaged in an instant.
"We do not ask them for permission."
In an article published on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee writes that "the mission [d'Inrupt] is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem in order to protect the integrity and quality of the new website built on Solid."
