The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
New research carried out in a Scottish Highlands area seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these single flying mammals and will guide future conservation activities.
The study of researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton in Inverewe Garden, Western Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to monitor the activity of bats throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using portable detectors.
Professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat screams and the activities of different species.
A map and a report on habitat will be prepared to prepare a detailed chart of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each of these species.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work such as grassland creation and the best way to preserve forests for bats and other associated species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, the populations of bats have declined considerably in the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects perch and results in habitat loss.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can the paper kill-mouses and some chemical treatments of construction materials, as well as the attacks of company cats.
The bats aren't really blind.
However, given their nightly hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use sophisticated echolocation technique to identify insects and obstacles to their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 large gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, inspection by the perch and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established the first and only reserve of Scottish bats on the site of Thrave in Dumfries-et-Galloway, which houses eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the domain manager, claims that the site is the ideal territory for them.
"Here, in Thrave, we have an ideal place for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still much to learn about bats, so that the work we do here and in other places will help us to better understand what bats need to thrive."
It stresses the importance of verifying the presence of bats before the maintenance of properties, because by destroying a single maternity nest without it, the death of 400 female and small, or even the disappearance of an entire local population, can result.
The bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their perchoirs.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scotland's head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: "We still have much to learn about our bats and about many of our species, we don't know what's going on in their populations for now."
