Point information on the red tide: Lower concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fisheries and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in certain areas of the Tampa Bay region.
According to the CPF, more irregular flowering conditions are reported in the areas of the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier - which causes fear of decreasing concentrations.
The red tide covers approximately 209 km (130 miles) of coastlines, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
There are islands about 16 km (10 miles) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer sites than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations in or off Pinellas County were reported last week, low to high concentrations across Hillsborough County, higher concentrations in Manatee County, higher concentrations in the bottom of Sarasota County or offshore, medium concentrations in Charlotte County and low concentrations in Lee County and across Lee County, high concentrations in the bottom or wide of Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation persist in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory irritation was reported in northwestern Florida during the past week.
